00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:07.960
been seen before and insight.

00:44:07.960 --> 00:44:09.610
And it's just that
hunger and quest

00:44:09.610 --> 00:44:13.000
for how much more can we
have storytelling change us?

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:15.800
And I think in that
quest for learning,

00:44:15.800 --> 00:44:17.600
you're transformed yourself.

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:19.970
And I would say stay hungry.

00:44:19.970 --> 00:44:24.410
Stay foolish is super
important to do if you

00:44:24.410 --> 00:44:25.660
want to become something.

00:44:25.660 --> 00:44:27.410
There's a whole lot
of people that do just

00:44:27.410 --> 00:44:30.850
want to skate through life
and live on the system

00:44:30.850 --> 00:44:34.080
or live on a system or just
be plugged in to the matrix.

00:44:34.080 --> 00:44:37.020
Maybe not that system.

00:44:37.020 --> 00:44:39.220
But yeah, it's
just a mindset that

00:44:39.220 --> 00:44:41.820
will turn you from an individual
contributor to manager

00:44:41.820 --> 00:44:42.750
to leader.

00:44:42.750 --> 00:44:46.140
It's all a mindset.

00:44:46.140 --> 00:44:49.580
One of the reasons we
use the term torchbearer,

00:44:49.580 --> 00:44:50.710
because it's a mantle.

00:44:50.710 --> 00:44:52.370
Being a leader is a mantle.

00:44:52.370 --> 00:44:54.260
You're offered opportunities
to lead all day.

00:44:54.260 --> 00:44:56.030
Like, Frodo had the
little ring fall

00:44:56.030 --> 00:44:58.410
on his hand and
he's like, holy cow.

00:44:58.410 --> 00:45:00.730
Do I want to deal
with this or do I not?

00:45:00.730 --> 00:45:02.100
You're given a choice.

00:45:02.100 --> 00:45:03.650
And leadership's like that.

00:45:03.650 --> 00:45:04.570
it's like a mantle.

00:45:04.570 --> 00:45:08.080
And a lot of people
self-select out of leading.

00:45:08.080 --> 00:45:10.180
They self-select
out, and they choose

00:45:10.180 --> 00:45:13.062
to not follow, go into
the fire of Sauron.

00:45:13.062 --> 00:45:14.270
That is kind of scary, right?

00:45:14.270 --> 00:45:17.780
There's a lot of interesting
hardships in choosing to be

00:45:17.780 --> 00:45:20.160
a leader, but the ones that
communicate well have less

00:45:20.160 --> 00:45:22.626
hardships than the
ones that don't.

00:45:22.626 --> 00:45:25.030
AUDIENCE: So a gentle
follow-up, if I may.

00:45:25.030 --> 00:45:30.280
You mentioned printing out
tons of research and so on.

00:45:30.280 --> 00:45:34.600
NANCY DUARTE: We
only killed one tree.

00:45:34.600 --> 00:45:36.634
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:45:36.634 --> 00:45:38.550
AUDIENCE: Silent motivation
behind my question

00:45:38.550 --> 00:45:41.990
here was with the internet and
knowledge becoming so much more

00:45:41.990 --> 00:45:43.590
accessible, there's
also the concept

00:45:43.590 --> 00:45:46.490
of information overload.

00:45:46.490 --> 00:45:50.237
And in your works, and every
time you do so much research,

00:45:50.237 --> 00:45:52.070
I was wondering, how
do you balance learning

00:45:52.070 --> 00:45:53.936
versus information overload?

00:45:53.936 --> 00:45:57.047
NANCY DUARTE: We had a
round of this that we did

00:45:57.047 --> 00:45:58.380
and we pasted it up on the wall.

00:45:58.380 --> 00:46:00.595
We were real excited, and we
brought one of our key clients

00:46:00.595 --> 00:46:01.094
in.

00:46:01.094 --> 00:46:02.700
And he was like, holy cow.

00:46:02.700 --> 00:46:04.990
You guys have, like,
six books in here.

00:46:04.990 --> 00:46:08.980
You need to-- it's hard to
murder your own darlings,

00:46:08.980 --> 00:46:09.480
right?

00:46:09.480 --> 00:46:12.249
And you would get really
attached to stuff, especially

00:46:12.249 --> 00:46:13.290
when it's research-based.

00:46:13.290 --> 00:46:15.498
Because there were things
where I was like, for sure?

00:46:15.498 --> 00:46:17.590
We spent two months on
this one concept we cut.

00:46:17.590 --> 00:46:19.660
Two people times
two months cutting.

00:46:19.660 --> 00:46:22.410
That was hard, but it was right.

00:46:22.410 --> 00:46:25.880
And so you get so deep
you lose perspective.

00:46:25.880 --> 00:46:28.530
And we actually had other
people come in and slash

00:46:28.530 --> 00:46:29.610
and slash and slash.

00:46:29.610 --> 00:46:32.110
And we have some beautiful stuff
that's hit the cutting room

00:46:32.110 --> 00:46:33.700
floor that we're
just now next week,

00:46:33.700 --> 00:46:36.670
we're going away for the
whole week, to my house,

00:46:36.670 --> 00:46:40.015
to examine the things that got
cut to see if we can plant that

00:46:40.015 --> 00:46:41.390
and it blooms into
something new.

00:46:41.390 --> 00:46:44.470
But cutting it,
slashing that stuff-- I

00:46:44.470 --> 00:46:47.660
have a photo of her where
we pasted it up on the wall.

00:46:47.660 --> 00:46:50.510
PATTI SANCHEZ: It was like
"Home Alone." [SCREAMS]

00:46:50.510 --> 00:46:51.390
Very upsetting.

00:46:51.390 --> 00:46:53.410
NANCY DUARTE: We literally
took the whole thing.

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:55.480
And it was two months
before deadline.

00:46:55.480 --> 00:46:57.930
We cut half the
book and rebuilt it.

00:46:57.930 --> 00:46:58.932
It was unbelievable.

00:46:58.932 --> 00:47:00.932
PATTI SANCHEZ: But it was
the right thing to do,

00:47:00.932 --> 00:47:04.794
and what motivated it was a
desire to help the reader.

00:47:04.794 --> 00:47:06.460
The feedback that we
got from the people

00:47:06.460 --> 00:47:10.219
that we tested the ideas with,
that's what gave me conviction

00:47:10.219 --> 00:47:12.510
to let go of some things that
I was really attached to.

00:47:12.510 --> 00:47:13.968
Because it was more
important to me

00:47:13.968 --> 00:47:15.450
that they walk
away with something

00:47:15.450 --> 00:47:18.580
that's valuable to them
than to satisfy myself.

00:47:18.580 --> 00:47:21.190
NANCY DUARTE: Showcase that
we printed the internet wasn't

00:47:21.190 --> 00:47:22.330
as important.

00:47:22.330 --> 00:47:24.330
PATTI SANCHEZ: Some of
it came from in here too.

00:47:24.330 --> 00:47:25.746
It wasn't all out
in the internet.

00:47:28.740 --> 00:47:30.890
Any other questions
from you guys?

00:47:30.890 --> 00:47:33.420
Hope it is a really hard,
challenging question out there.

00:47:33.420 --> 00:47:35.878
NANCY DUARTE: Or you guys just
want to get back to your job

00:47:35.878 --> 00:47:37.842
and be torchbearers.

00:47:37.842 --> 00:47:39.790
AUDIENCE: I'm just
curious to hear about some

00:47:39.790 --> 00:47:42.225
of the company reinventions
you went through.

00:47:42.225 --> 00:47:43.279
NANCY DUARTE: Yeah.

00:47:43.279 --> 00:47:44.820
So believe it or
not, a lot of people

00:47:44.820 --> 00:47:46.910
think I started the
company, but my husband did.

00:47:46.910 --> 00:47:50.210
1987, he worked his
butt off all summer

00:47:50.210 --> 00:47:53.230
moving furniture from a
failing aerospace company.

00:47:53.230 --> 00:47:55.480
And he saved enough
to buy a Mac.

00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:57.730
And he started doing
technical illustrations.

00:47:57.730 --> 00:48:00.220
So he was a freelancer working
from home in his underwear,

00:48:00.220 --> 00:48:02.350
kids underfoot,
loving it, right?

00:48:02.350 --> 00:48:05.850
And then I joined him in
1990, pick up the phone,

00:48:05.850 --> 00:48:08.190
and in one afternoon
won three huge accounts.

00:48:08.190 --> 00:48:09.850
So I don't go back
to my real job.

00:48:09.850 --> 00:48:12.969
We become a service bureau I
actually had a 35 millimeter

00:48:12.969 --> 00:48:13.510
slide imager.

00:48:13.510 --> 00:48:14.610
People don't even
know what that was.

00:48:14.610 --> 00:48:15.400
Cost us 20 grand.

00:48:15.400 --> 00:48:18.260
Here we are in this crappy
apartment in Sunnyvale,

00:48:18.260 --> 00:48:20.000
with yellow shag carpet.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:22.710
And we have a $20,000
thing that makes slides.

00:48:22.710 --> 00:48:25.430
Every penny we made, we
stuck back in the business.

00:48:25.430 --> 00:48:27.370
So we became a service
bureau, and then we

00:48:27.370 --> 00:48:28.830
became a design firm.

00:48:28.830 --> 00:48:31.720
And then the dotcom
crash happened.

00:48:31.720 --> 00:48:34.120
Good to Great came
out, and Good to Great

00:48:34.120 --> 00:48:35.385
had a hedgehog concept.

00:48:35.385 --> 00:48:37.260
And it said, if there's
one thing you can do,

00:48:37.260 --> 00:48:38.718
you can be best in
the world at, be

00:48:38.718 --> 00:48:42.196
profitable at and passionate
about, do just that one thing.

00:48:42.196 --> 00:48:44.320
So here was a season where
the economy had crashed,

00:48:44.320 --> 00:48:47.150
and I did the most
counterintuitive dream,

00:48:47.150 --> 00:48:49.790
re-dream of my business
ever, is I completely

00:48:49.790 --> 00:48:51.500
shut the door on print and web.

00:48:51.500 --> 00:48:53.830
And we did just
presentations, the one thing

00:48:53.830 --> 00:48:55.380
that we could focus on.

00:48:55.380 --> 00:48:57.440
So then we became a
niche, and then we

00:48:57.440 --> 00:48:59.970
became best in the world when
we produced our material.

00:48:59.970 --> 00:49:02.110
And then we decided to
become best in the world

00:49:02.110 --> 00:49:03.550
at business storytelling.

00:49:03.550 --> 00:49:05.050
And then you can
see-- and now we're

00:49:05.050 --> 00:49:06.230
in leading through stories.

00:49:06.230 --> 00:49:09.087
So you can see the migration
of how that happened.

00:49:09.087 --> 00:49:10.670
PATTI SANCHEZ: And
we're not done yet.

00:49:10.670 --> 00:49:12.211
NANCY DUARTE: And
we're not done yet.

00:49:12.211 --> 00:49:14.950
The cool thing is, we moved in
two years ago to the building

00:49:14.950 --> 00:49:17.970
that my husband moved
furniture from in 1987.

00:49:17.970 --> 00:49:20.570
So the building we're in, and
then the four buildings to 101

00:49:20.570 --> 00:49:22.605
are the ones that he
moved furniture from.

00:49:22.605 --> 00:49:24.230
PATTI SANCHEZ: One
of the things that I

00:49:24.230 --> 00:49:28.120
love about that story, the
transformation around 2001

00:49:28.120 --> 00:49:31.136
and focusing on presentations
is saying no to other things.

00:49:31.136 --> 00:49:32.510
Nancy talked about
the importance

00:49:32.510 --> 00:49:33.650
of endings and beginnings.

00:49:33.650 --> 00:49:35.566
And I think that's
actually one of the hardest

00:49:35.566 --> 00:49:37.790
things about
reinvention of yourself

00:49:37.790 --> 00:49:41.040
or anything that you're working
on is saying no to something,

00:49:41.040 --> 00:49:44.260
leaving that something behind.

00:49:44.260 --> 00:49:48.407
But it's also freeing too,
lets you do bigger things.

00:49:48.407 --> 00:49:50.490
NANCY DUARTE: So if someone
has a burning question

00:49:50.490 --> 00:49:52.198
and throws their hands
up, we'll take it.

00:49:52.198 --> 00:49:54.240
Otherwise, you guys get to go.

00:49:54.240 --> 00:49:57.190
Rehydrate and get ready
for your next thing.

